Hey @templar・3 , just wanted to provide more insight into the data format of the upcoming run!

As we scale up to larger models, we need more data for the hungry model to consume. For the next run we'll have 6x more data, with about 2TB of storage required for everything on disk. At the largest model sizes, we'll need even more than that! 

With our miners and validators in mind, we wanted to avoid disk storage pressure but maintain the advantages of having the data locally. To do that, we will be blocking the download of the first ~200GB shard (S1). We're seeing this should take about 20m under the current codebase defaults, assuming ~150 cpus. The next shard will download in the background (S2). 

At the end of the allocated windows, the dataset manager from PR #440 will swap the datasets and the dataloader will be refreshed. The upcoming shard (S3) will automatically download in the background. And so on through the end of the training run (S4:). 

The shards will be hosted thanks to @AdamW and we'll provide the env keys for the access. If you'd like, you can use the CloudFlare migration tool to self-host the shards. If you have ample storage, you can also keep all the shards on disk. We'll provide a readme ahead of the training.

PR #440 is being finalized and merged. The final shard is being written (100B tokens left to write!) and we'll be writing the sample_ids to complement the shards for the sampler. We'll also be able to provide clarification on any changes for running the validator via the dockerfile

As a result, we anticipate that the next training run will start Saturday, August 2, 2025 1:00:00 PM !!

Just to elaborate a bit on what we did. In SN9 and SN29 there was a cap on model size and within that space we had to squeeze out performance, on a specific dataset. So we looked where to cut out weights, because the freed up weights could then be put to practical use. _In that context_ we found that some tokens were never used - they did not occur in _that_ dataset. So we were able to eliminate those tokens - and the associated weights in `lm_head` and `embed_tokens` - while keeping loss values equal, and used the freed up weights to grow the model in other dimensions.

Now I don't know what you guys are doing here, so I cannot say if it makes any sense to apply these principles. We simply looked at the code and the data, and optimized it a bit.

So basically the `global_shard_x_of_10` that you currently have will be quite small by comparison to the current 10 shards. The previous dataset was 1/6th the token count of this current dataset. We now have 1 trillion tokens to train on, which increases the length of time that we can train without seeing the same data. This is a proxy for training quality, as most LLM training runs do only 1 pass over the entirety of the dataset. 

The other issue is that the indices that you would train on would be different than those available to the validator

Deciding to share the dataset was less of a design decision than making it so that it does not need downloaded and processed. Since the current dataset is >2TB on disk, combining the shards in that way would require 4TB of disk space. As always with rate limiting and such, YMMV, so we decided to provide guidance for using the CloudFlare Migration tool so that there is not a conflict inre: rate limitations
